Introduction

Urban Ministries of Durham (UMD) is a non-profit organization that serves its community by offering servies that help reduce the rate of homelessness in Durham, NC. The website for UMD is www.umdurham.org. One service UMD offers is shelter. This service is meant to provide struggling individuals or families with a safe place to stay until they are able to get on their own. In the meantime, UMD provides resources to help this happen, such as helping with finding jobs or providing professional clothes for interviews, etc.

Data Cleaning

There is a lot of data from UMD regarding who enters and exits the shelter resource of the organization. This data identifies each individual as a client, and records ones age, gender, ethnicity, race, entry and exit dates, and reasons for leaving UMD, as well as other data collection. For this project, we focus on any association between duration of stay at UMD and gender, race, ethnicity, and age at entry. We define duration of stay as number of nights spent at UMD, calculated from the date of entry and the date of exit. We merge the two datasets and preprocess the two datasets in python. For this project, we remove any data with missing data, since the fraction of those with any missing data is less than 1%. In the end, we have a total of 5189 observations.

In the plots below, we can see that age is generally normally distributed. The age with the most number of clients is around 50. There are more people aged 50 and below than above 50.

There are more males than females, and more females than transgendered females. Since the proportion of transgengered females is very low (about 0.33%), we will remove transgendered female observations from our analysis.
